Here's the recommended approach using a custom `Window` subclass with `OnStopped` / `OnResumed` / `OnDestroying`:

**1. Create a custom Window (`AppWindow.cs`)**

```csharp
public class AppWindow : Window
{
    public AppWindow(Page page) : base(page) { }

    protected override void OnStopped()
    {
        base.OnStopped();
        if (Page is AppShell shell)
        {
            var vm = GetNoteViewModel(shell);
            if (vm != null)
                Preferences.Set("draft_text", vm.DraftText);
        }
    }

    protected override void OnResumed()
    {
        base.OnResumed();
        if (Page is AppShell shell)
        {
            var vm = GetNoteViewModel(shell);
            if (vm != null)
                vm.DraftText = Preferences.Get("draft_text", string.Empty);
        }
    }

    protected override void OnDestroying()
    {
        base.OnDestroying();
        // Android back-button can skip Stopped entirely
        if (Page is AppShell shell)
        {
            var vm = GetNoteViewModel(shell);
            if (vm != null)
                Preferences.Set("draft_text", vm.DraftText);
        }
    }

    private NoteViewModel? GetNoteViewModel(AppShell shell)
        => (shell.CurrentPage?.BindingContext) as NoteViewModel;
}
```

**2. Return it from `App.CreateWindow`**

```csharp
// App.xaml.cs
protected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)
    => new AppWindow(new AppShell());
```

**3. Restore on first launch too (in your page or VM)**

```csharp
public NoteViewModel()
{
    DraftText = Preferences.Get("draft_text", string.Empty);
}
```

### Key things to know

| Gotcha | Why it matters |
|---|---|
| Save in **both** `OnStopped` and `OnDestroying` | Android's back button can skip `Stopped` and go straight to `Destroying` |
| `OnResumed` doesn't fire on first launch | Initial sequence is `Created → Activated`, so load the draft in your constructor too |
| Keep handlers fast (<1-2s) | Slow work triggers ANR on Android or watchdog kills on iOS — `Preferences` is ideal for small values |
| Don't save in `OnDeactivated` | That fires for transient focus loss (notification shade, dialogs) — not actual backgrounding |
